Model Comparison Interpretation\n","XGBoost delivers the best predictive performance, achieving the lowest RMSE and MAE. This shows that incorporating nonlinear relationships and interaction effects improves demand forecasting beyond simple approaches.\n","\n","The historical baseline remains surprisingly strong, confirming that recent sales history is the dominant signal in retail demand. Most predictive power comes from demand momentum rather than complex features.\n","\n","The regression model performs worst in prediction, but serves an important role by providing an interpretable estimate of price elasticity.\n","\n","Chronos performs reasonably well using only past sales data, but does not outperform XGBoost. Because it was evaluated on a smaller sampled subset, it should be treated as a benchmark rather than a directly comparable result.\n","\n","Overall, the results suggest that demand is highly predictable from recent behavior, and while advanced models improve accuracy, most of the signal is already present in the data."],"metadata":{"id":"rvryihkD4VJ9"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Important Comparison Note\n","\n","Chronos was evaluated on a sampled subset of item-store series using a fixed 28-day horizon, while XGBoost, the baseline, and the regression model were evaluated on the full time-based test split. As a result, Chronos should be interpreted as a benchmark reference rather than a strictly comparable final ranking."],"metadata":{"id":"8LxpgY9S4YWG"}}]}